{
  "local_port": 37664,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some good sources for free instrumental music to use in video tutorials?",
  "response": "Creating engaging video tutorials often benefits from high-quality instrumental music that enhances the learning experience without distracting viewers. Fortunately, there are numerous sources offering free instrumental music tailored for such uses. Below are some reputable platforms where you can find free instrumental tracks, along with important details about their licenses and usage terms:\n\n### 1. **YouTube Audio Library**\n- **Website:** [YouTube Audio Library](https://www.youtube.com/audiolibrary/music)\n- **Features:**\n  - Extensive collection of free music and sound effects.\n  - Easy to search by genre, mood, instrument, duration, and attribution requirements.\n  - Tracks are free to use in any YouTube videos, and many can also be used in external projects.\n- **License:** Varies; some tracks require attribution. Be sure to check each track\u2019s specific license terms.\n\n### 2. **Free Music Archive (FMA)**\n- **Website:** [Free Music Archive](https://freemusicarchive.org/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Curated library of high-quality, legal audio downloads.\n  - Diverse genres and styles, including many instrumental options suitable for tutorials.\n  - Search and filter based on license type to fit your project needs.\n- **License:** Primarily Creative Commons licenses. Check individual track licenses for permissions and attribution requirements.\n\n### 3. **Incompetech**\n- **Website:** [Incompetech](https://incompetech.com/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Created by composer Kevin MacLeod, offering a vast selection of royalty-free music.\n  - Easy navigation by genre, feel, or length.\n  - Popular among YouTubers and content creators for its versatility.\n- **License:** Free to use with attribution under Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 License. A license can be purchased to use without attribution.\n\n### 4. **Bensound**\n- **Website:** [Bensound](https://www.bensound.com/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Collection of original music composed by Benjamin Tissot.\n  - Wide range of genres, including acoustic, cinematic, and electronic.\n  - User-friendly interface with preview options.\n- **License:** Free to use under Creative Commons Attribution-NoDerivs 3.0 License (requires credit). Licensing options available for purchase to remove attribution requirements.\n\n### 5. **Purple Planet Music**\n- **Website:** [Purple Planet Music](https://www.purple-planet.com/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Offers a variety of instrumental tracks suitable for backgrounds, tutorials, and presentations.\n  - Organized by mood and theme for easy selection.\n  - High-quality, professionally composed music.\n- **License:** Free to use with attribution under Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 License. Commercial licenses can be purchased to use without attribution.\n\n### 6. **Epidemic Sound (Free Trial)**\n- **Website:** [Epidemic Sound](https://www.epidemicsound.com/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Massive library of high-quality, exclusive tracks and sound effects.\n  - Regularly updated with new music across numerous genres.\n  - Advanced search and filtering options.\n- **License:** Primarily a subscription-based service, but offers a free trial period. Ensure to review licensing terms, especially regarding long-term use after the trial ends.\n\n### 7. **ccMixter**\n- **Website:** [ccMixter](https://ccmixter.org/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Community-driven site with user-generated music samples and remixes.\n  - A good selection of instrumental tracks suitable for tutorials.\n  - Option to search specifically for royalty-free music.\n- **License:** Varies; many tracks are available under Creative Commons licenses. Always check the specific license of each track for usage permissions and attribution requirements.\n\n### 8. **SoundCloud (Creative Commons)**\n- **Website:** [SoundCloud](https://soundcloud.com/)\n- **Features:**\n  - Millions of tracks uploaded by artists worldwide.\n  - Use the search filters to find music licensed under Creative Commons.\n  - Diverse range of genres and styles, including instrumental options.\n- **License:** Depends on the artist; use the Creative Commons filter to find tracks you can legally use. Always verify the specific licensing terms on each track\u2019s page.\n\n### Tips for Using Free Instrumental Music:\n- **Check Licensing:** Always review the specific license associated with each track to ensure it fits your intended use, especially for commercial projects.\n- **Provide Attribution When Required:** If a license requires you to credit the artist, include the necessary information clearly in your video\u2019s description or credits section.\n- **Avoid Copyright Claims:** Using music without proper licensing can lead to videos being muted, taken down, or monetization being claimed by the rights holder. Always adhere to licensing terms to prevent such issues.\n- **Consider Subscription Services for More Options:** If your project requires extensive and diverse music options without attribution, consider investing in a subscription-based service like Epidemic Sound or Artlist for broader access and additional licensing benefits.\n\nBy leveraging these resources, you can enhance your video tutorials with fitting instrumental music while respecting creators' rights and maintaining compliance with licensing requirements.",
